  <!-- ============ ESTRATEGIA: TEXTOS LARGOS ============ -->
  <section class="ec-section" id="estrategia">
    <div class="ec-wrap">
      <span class="ec-kicker"><i class="bi bi-compass"></i> Estrategia · Antes de las preguntas</span>
      <h2>Cómo escuchar un audio largo</h2>
      <p>En Media los audios duran más y van a velocidad natural. Si intentas <strong>traducir palabra por palabra</strong>, te quedas atrás y pierdes el hilo. La comprensión auditiva se gana <strong>antes</strong> de que empiece a sonar (anticipando lo que se pedirá) y se ordena <strong>mientras</strong> escuchas (capturando lo importante y soltando lo accesorio).</p>

      <article class="ec-card" id="c-textos-largos">
        <header><div class="ix"><i class="bi bi-arrows-angle-expand"></i></div><div><h3>Idea global primero, detalles después</h3></div><button class="ec-done"></button></header>
        <div class="body">
          <div class="note base">
            <span class="lbl"><i class="bi bi-mortarboard-fill"></i> Desde cero</span>
            <p>Un buen oyente no entiende cada palabra: <strong>predice y filtra</strong>. Con un audio largo conviene escuchar en dos capas:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Primera capa &mdash; idea global (<em>gist</em>):</strong> ¿de qué trata?, ¿quién habla y a quién?, ¿con qué intención? Responde preguntas como <em>"What is the recording mainly about?"</em> o <em>"What kind of text is it?"</em>.</li>
              <li><strong>Segunda capa &mdash; detalles clave:</strong> rastrea los datos puntuales que pidan las preguntas (una fecha, un nombre, una cifra, una razón). Engancha cada dato a su pista: un año con un hecho, un nombre con un cargo.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Lee las preguntas <strong>antes</strong> de que suene el audio: te dicen qué buscar y activan el vocabulario del tema. Y si pierdes una frase, <strong>suéltala y sigue</strong>: la idea se recupera por el contexto que viene después. Quedarte "pegado" en una palabra te hace perder las tres frases siguientes.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="note ojo">
            <span class="lbl"><i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle-fill"></i> El error típico</span>
            <p>Elegir la alternativa que contiene una <strong>palabra que sí escuchaste</strong>, aunque diga algo distinto. La ECEP pone distractores con datos "casi correctos": hay que verificar que el <em>significado completo</em> de la frase coincida con el audio, no solo que aparezca una palabra conocida.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">A long recording at natural speed contains several names, dates and figures. A question asks <em>"What is the recording mainly about?"</em> Which listening strategy fits this question best?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> Translating each sentence into Spanish before deciding on the answer.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> Writing down every number you hear and choosing the one repeated most often.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> Listening for the overall idea (gist): the topic, who is speaking and with what intention.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> Focusing only on the very last sentence and ignoring the rest.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: C.</strong> Una pregunta de idea central ("mainly about") pide <strong>escucha global</strong>: el tema y el sentido general, no un dato suelto. <strong>A</strong> es contraproducente: traducir palabra por palabra te atrasa. <strong>B</strong> y <strong>D</strong> son escucha de detalle parcial, útil para otras preguntas, no para captar el sentido global.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ ESTRATEGIA: TOMAR NOTAS ============ -->
  <section class="ec-section" id="notas" style="padding-top:8px">
    <div class="ec-wrap">
      <article class="ec-card" id="c-tomar-notas">
        <header><div class="ix"><i class="bi bi-pencil"></i></div><div><h3>Tomar notas breves, no transcribir</h3></div><button class="ec-done"></button></header>
        <div class="body">
          <div class="note base">
            <span class="lbl"><i class="bi bi-mortarboard-fill"></i> Desde cero</span>
            <p>En un audio largo no puedes anotarlo todo. Toma <strong>notas mínimas y abreviadas</strong> de lo que probablemente se pregunte:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Datos duros:</strong> fechas, años, cifras, precios y nombres propios (con su pista al lado: <em>"1939 &rarr; Batman"</em>, <em>"1,075,000 USD &rarr; auction 2010"</em>).</li>
              <li><strong>Marcadores de estructura:</strong> palabras que ordenan el discurso (<em>first, then, however, because, so</em>) te avisan dónde viene una causa, un contraste o una conclusión.</li>
              <li><strong>Idea de cada bloque:</strong> una palabra clave por tema, no la frase completa. Anota el <em>sentido</em>, no la traducción.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>La meta es <strong>capturar la idea y los detalles clave</strong>, no producir una transcripción. Si escribes demasiado, dejas de escuchar.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="note dato">
            <span class="lbl"><i class="bi bi-lightbulb-fill"></i> Dato</span>
            <p>Los <strong>números y nombres propios</strong> casi siempre vienen con una pista que los ancla: un año junto a un hecho (<em>"on 30 March 1939"</em>), una cifra con su unidad (<em>"800,000 copies"</em>), un nombre con un cargo (<em>"host Johnny Carson"</em>). Engancha cada dato a su pista para no confundirlo con otro número del audio.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">During a long recording you have to answer a later question about an exact date. What is the most efficient way to take notes while listening?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> Try to write down every word the speaker says, like a full transcript.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> Jot down only key data &mdash; dates, names, figures &mdash; each next to the event it refers to.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> Write nothing and rely entirely on memory until the questions appear.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> Draw the speaker and the studio to remember the scene.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: B.</strong> En un audio largo conviene anotar <strong>solo los datos clave</strong> (fechas, nombres, cifras) junto al hecho al que pertenecen, para recuperarlos después. <strong>A</strong> es imposible a velocidad natural y te impide escuchar; <strong>C</strong> sobrecarga la memoria con tanta información; <strong>D</strong> no aporta nada para responder una fecha.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>


  <!-- ============ AUDIO 1: ENTREVISTA ============ -->
  <section class="ec-section" id="audio1">
    <div class="ec-wrap">
      <article class="ec-card">
        <header><div class="ix"><i class="bi bi-headphones"></i></div><div><h3>Audio 1 &mdash; Entrevista a un actor (examen ECEP 2024)</h3></div><button class="ec-done"></button></header>
        <div class="body">
          <div class="note prueba"><span class="lbl"><i class="bi bi-soundwave"></i> Listening auténtico</span><p>Audio <strong>real</strong> del examen ECEP de Inglés (Educación Media, 2024): un entrevistador conversa con un actor sobre las <strong>decisiones</strong> que toma y cómo entiende la publicidad de sus películas. Escúchalo, intenta responder sin leer la transcripción y luego revísala.</p></div>
          <figure class="ec-fig" style="margin-top:0">
            <audio controls preload="none" style="width:100%;display:block;border-radius:12px"><source src="/audio/ecep/ingles/media-rec1.mp3" type="audio/mpeg">Tu navegador no soporta el audio.</audio>
            <figcaption>Audio · Educación Media Inglés (CPEIP, 2024). Liberado para docentes.</figcaption>
          </figure>
          <details style="margin-top:14px;background:var(--ec-surface,#fff);border:1px solid var(--ec-line,#e5e7eb);border-radius:12px;padding:12px 16px">
            <summary style="cursor:pointer;font-weight:600;color:var(--d-ing-ink)">Ver transcripción (Transcript)</summary>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;line-height:1.7;font-size:14.5px">You talked earlier about the choices you make, and not only in the films you do, but what you're saying. And it's true: when you come along into a place where you know you've been one of the biggest blockbusters of all time, it gives you this incredible opportunity to have a voice, and what you do with that really says something about you as a person. Like, when you go out to publicity on a film, do you look at that as an opportunity?</p>
            <p style="line-height:1.7;font-size:14.5px">Not every time, and not with every film specifically. I mean, I do look at every moment as an opportunity, you know &mdash; whether we're sitting on the floor with our kids or we're doing an interview, everything's an opportunity to connect and communicate. So that interests me the most: to try to be as present and honest as I can be in those moments. I never want anything to feel false, or not be another moment to hopefully be even more truthful. That's the fun of it &mdash; and you gotta have fun, because a press junket ain't no fun. I mean, it's so exhausting, you can't believe how a press junket would be more exhausting than any movie anyone could do. But you know, you're sitting like this, and every four minutes someone else is coming in with the same exact three questions. So to really try to be authentic and have fun with it &mdash; I think it's fair and interesting.</p>
            <p style="line-height:1.7;font-size:14.5px">And you being a salesman &mdash; and we are all salesmen of our work, of our wares &mdash; but when you add to it that you're six or seven weeks out from people voting for the next president of the United States, and you have a film like <em>Recount</em> that's speaking about making sure your real vote actually counts, that's an incredible platform.</p>
            <p style="opacity:.6;font-size:12.5px;margin-top:8px">Transcripción del audio del examen CPEIP 2024, adaptada para lectura (uso educativo).</p>
          </details>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">What is the conversation mainly about?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> How to act in a blockbuster film and become famous.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> The actor's view on the choices he makes and how he uses publicity as an opportunity to connect.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> A detailed plot summary of the film <em>Recount</em>.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> The technical process of editing a movie before its release.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: B.</strong> Toda la conversación gira en torno a las <em>choices</em> del actor y a cómo ve la publicidad como una <em>"opportunity to connect and communicate"</em>. <strong>A</strong> y <strong>D</strong> no se tratan (no enseña a actuar ni a editar). <strong>C</strong> solo se nombra <em>Recount</em> al final como ejemplo, no se resume su trama.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">According to the actor, how does he describe a press junket?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> Relaxing and easy compared with filming.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> Something he refuses to do.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> A chance to meet the next president of the United States.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> Extremely exhausting, with the same three questions repeated again and again.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: D.</strong> Dice que un press junket <em>"ain't no fun&hellip; it's so exhausting"</em> y que <em>"every four minutes someone else is coming in with the same exact three questions"</em>. <strong>A</strong> contradice <em>exhausting</em>; <strong>B</strong> es falso, sí lo hace; <strong>C</strong> mezcla la mención de las elecciones al final, que es otro punto.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">When the actor says <em>"we are all salesmen of our work, of our wares,"</em> what does he most probably mean?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> That every actor secretly owns a shop.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> That promoting our own work is part of what we all do, himself included.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> That he dislikes anyone who sells products.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> That films should be given away for free.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: B.</strong> Por contexto, <em>"salesmen of our work, of our wares"</em> es una metáfora: <strong>todos promovemos nuestro propio trabajo</strong>, y él se incluye. <strong>A</strong> toma <em>salesman</em> de forma literal; <strong>C</strong> y <strong>D</strong> no se desprenden del audio (no rechaza a nadie ni habla de regalar películas).</div>
          </div>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">Why does the actor consider the film <em>Recount</em> "an incredible platform"?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> Because it was the highest-grossing blockbuster of all time.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> Because it came out six or seven weeks before a US presidential vote and deals with making sure your vote really counts.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> Because it was filmed entirely on the floor with his kids.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> Because the press junket for it was finally enjoyable.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: B.</strong> Explica que estaba <em>"six or seven weeks out from people voting for the next president"</em> y que <em>Recount</em> habla de <em>"making sure your real vote actually counts"</em>: por eso es una gran plataforma. <strong>A</strong>, <strong>C</strong> y <strong>D</strong> no se dicen del film (lo del piso y los hijos era otro ejemplo de "momento", y el press junket lo describe como agotador).</div>
          </div>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">What is the communicative situation of this recording?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> An interview, in which an interviewer asks an actor about his choices and he answers.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> A single narrator reading a news report.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> A scripted advertisement promoting a new car.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> A set of spoken instructions for an exam.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: A.</strong> Hay un entrevistador que plantea <em>"do you look at that as an opportunity?"</em> y un actor que responde extensamente: es una <strong>entrevista</strong>. <strong>C</strong> y <strong>D</strong> tendrían otro registro y finalidad; <strong>B</strong> exigiría un único narrador, pero aquí dialogan dos voces.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>


  <!-- ============ AUDIO 2: CINE ROMÁNTICO ============ -->
  <section class="ec-section" id="audio2" style="padding-top:8px">
    <div class="ec-wrap">
      <article class="ec-card">
        <header><div class="ix"><i class="bi bi-headphones"></i></div><div><h3>Audio 2 &mdash; &iquest;Por qué el cine es romántico? (examen ECEP 2024)</h3></div><button class="ec-done"></button></header>
        <div class="body">
          <div class="note prueba"><span class="lbl"><i class="bi bi-soundwave"></i> Listening auténtico</span><p>Audio <strong>real</strong> del examen ECEP de Inglés (Educación Media, 2024): un Q&amp;A que responde por qué ir al cine sigue siendo una cita romántica y da <strong>consejos</strong> para una buena salida. Escúchalo, intenta responder sin leer la transcripción y luego revísala.</p></div>
          <figure class="ec-fig" style="margin-top:0">
            <audio controls preload="none" style="width:100%;display:block;border-radius:12px"><source src="/audio/ecep/ingles/media-rec2.mp3" type="audio/mpeg">Tu navegador no soporta el audio.</audio>
            <figcaption>Audio · Educación Media Inglés (CPEIP, 2024). Liberado para docentes.</figcaption>
          </figure>
          <details style="margin-top:14px;background:var(--ec-surface,#fff);border:1px solid var(--ec-line,#e5e7eb);border-radius:12px;padding:12px 16px">
            <summary style="cursor:pointer;font-weight:600;color:var(--d-ing-ink)">Ver transcripción (Transcript)</summary>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;line-height:1.7;font-size:14.5px">Why is going to the cinema so romantic? Thanks for asking. As date-night options go, the cinema is a timeless classic which can be both fun and romantic. Even in the age of Netflix and chill, there's an appeal to the immersive experience you can only get watching a film on the big screen. So if you're wondering what to do this Valentine's Day&hellip;</p>
            <p style="line-height:1.7;font-size:14.5px">During the film you can interpret body language. If it's a first date and they're on the phone all the time, that might be off-putting. If your date is comfortable enough to hold your hand, or let you put your arm around their shoulder without it being awkward, that's a good sign. Of course, don't be pushy or intrusive: make sure you ask your date for consent before trying any kind of physical intimacy, even if you are already in an established relationship with the person. Being next to your date in a dimly lit room can also be romantic, as it lets you snuggle up close to one another. Watching a film can take us through a lot of emotions, and being at the cinema only intensifies them; sharing that experience with someone can be a great way of building a connection.</p>
            <p style="line-height:1.7;font-size:14.5px">Our first piece of advice is to take care of the organisation: choose the cinema, film and screening time, but make sure it's a genre your partner actually likes. Depending on how long you've known each other, that may mean inquiring about their tastes. For example, if horror films terrify them, you'll want to know in advance, so you don't make the mistake of picking one. The best idea is to find something that will appeal to both of you, so you can share your feelings about it after the film is over.</p>
            <p style="line-height:1.7;font-size:14.5px">And of course, regular date etiquette applies. Don't be late! Leave yourself plenty of time to buy snacks on your way in, and then have your choice of seats. You'll also want to talk about the film and get to know each other better, or make plans for the next date. That may depend on what time the film screening ends, so think things through and have a get-out plan in case the date goes badly. There you have it! Now you know why going to the cinema is so romantic.</p>
            <p style="opacity:.6;font-size:12.5px;margin-top:8px">Transcripción del audio del examen CPEIP 2024, adaptada para lectura (uso educativo).</p>
          </details>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">What is the main purpose of this recording?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> To explain why the cinema is a romantic date option and to give advice for a good date.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> To review a specific horror film released on Valentine's Day.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> To sell tickets for a particular cinema chain.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> To compare the prices of Netflix and the cinema.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: A.</strong> El audio responde la pregunta inicial &mdash;por qué el cine es romántico&mdash; y luego da <strong>consejos</strong> para una buena cita. <strong>B</strong> usa "horror" solo como ejemplo de un género a evitar; <strong>C</strong> no promociona ninguna cadena; <strong>D</strong> menciona "Netflix and chill" de pasada, sin comparar precios.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">According to the speaker, what should you do before any kind of physical intimacy on a date?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> Turn off the lights in the cinema.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> Buy snacks for both of you.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> Choose a horror film to break the ice.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> Ask your date for consent first.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: D.</strong> El texto es explícito: <em>"make sure you ask your date for consent before trying any kind of physical intimacy"</em>, incluso en una relación ya establecida. <strong>A</strong>, <strong>B</strong> y <strong>C</strong> son detalles de otros consejos (la sala con poca luz, comprar snacks, evitar el terror), no la condición que se pide antes de la intimidad física.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">What is the speaker's first piece of advice for organising the date?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> Always pick a horror film to test your partner's courage.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> Choose the cinema, film and time, making sure it's a genre your partner actually likes.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> Sit as far away from your date as possible.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> Avoid talking about the film once it is over.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: B.</strong> El primer consejo es <em>"take care of the organisation: choose the cinema, film and screening time, but make sure it's a genre your partner actually likes"</em>. <strong>A</strong> es lo contrario (advierte evitar el terror si asusta a la pareja); <strong>C</strong> contradice el "snuggle up close"; <strong>D</strong> también, porque sugiere hablar del film después.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">The speaker advises you to "have a <em>get-out plan</em> in case the date goes badly." In this context, a <em>get-out plan</em> is:</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> a plan to leave the cinema before the film ends.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> a way of getting out of the relationship forever.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> a backup idea to end the date politely if it isn't going well.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> a discount plan for cheaper cinema tickets.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: C.</strong> Por contexto, tras hablar de planes para "la próxima cita", un <em>get-out plan</em> es una <strong>idea de reserva para terminar la cita con elegancia</strong> si va mal. <strong>A</strong> toma "get out" demasiado literal (salir del cine); <strong>B</strong> exagera el alcance; <strong>D</strong> introduce descuentos que el audio no menciona.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">Why does the speaker say being next to your date "in a dimly lit room" can be romantic?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> Because it lets you snuggle up close and share the emotions of the film.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> Because the dark hides the price of the tickets.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> Because it is easier to use your phone unnoticed.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> Because horror films are scarier in the dark.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: A.</strong> El audio dice que la sala poco iluminada <em>"lets you snuggle up close to one another"</em> y que compartir las emociones del film <em>"can be a great way of building a connection"</em>. <strong>B</strong>, <strong>C</strong> y <strong>D</strong> no se mencionan; de hecho, el texto critica estar "on the phone all the time".</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>


  <!-- ============ AUDIO 3: BATMAN ============ -->
  <section class="ec-section" id="audio3" style="padding-top:8px">
    <div class="ec-wrap">
      <article class="ec-card">
        <header><div class="ix"><i class="bi bi-headphones"></i></div><div><h3>Audio 3 &mdash; La primera aparición de Batman (examen ECEP 2024)</h3></div><button class="ec-done"></button></header>
        <div class="body">
          <div class="note prueba"><span class="lbl"><i class="bi bi-soundwave"></i> Listening auténtico</span><p>Audio <strong>real</strong> del examen ECEP de Inglés (Educación Media, 2024): un episodio de podcast tipo <em>HistoryPod</em> que relata cuándo y cómo apareció Batman por primera vez en <em>Detective Comics</em> N.&deg; 27. Escúchalo, intenta responder sin leer la transcripción y luego revísala.</p></div>
          <figure class="ec-fig" style="margin-top:0">
            <audio controls preload="none" style="width:100%;display:block;border-radius:12px"><source src="/audio/ecep/ingles/media-rec3.mp3" type="audio/mpeg">Tu navegador no soporta el audio.</audio>
            <figcaption>Audio · Educación Media Inglés (CPEIP, 2024). Liberado para docentes.</figcaption>
          </figure>
          <details style="margin-top:14px;background:var(--ec-surface,#fff);border:1px solid var(--ec-line,#e5e7eb);border-radius:12px;padding:12px 16px">
            <summary style="cursor:pointer;font-weight:600;color:var(--d-ing-ink)">Ver transcripción (Transcript)</summary>
            <p style="margin-top:10px;line-height:1.7;font-size:14.5px">Hello, and welcome to HistoryPod. On 30 March 1939 Batman made his first appearance when <em>Detective Comics</em> No. 27 went on sale. The first issue of <em>Detective Comics</em> had appeared in March 1937 and featured an anthology of hard-boiled detective stories. It was the third series to be released by National Allied Publications, which had already experienced enormous success with Superman. The publisher was looking to include more superheroes in its comics to meet the public's demand.</p>
            <p style="line-height:1.7;font-size:14.5px">Batman was created by Bob Kane and Bill Finger, and first appeared in a story called <em>The Case of the Chemical Syndicate</em>, along with Commissioner Gordon. In the story, the Bat-Man solves the death of a chemical manufacturer; at the end he is revealed to readers as the alter ego of Bruce Wayne. Subsequent issues of <em>Detective Comics</em> led to him being given his own title in 1940. Within a year, the comic was selling 800,000 copies every issue.</p>
            <p style="line-height:1.7;font-size:14.5px">Although the cover date for the first issue was May 1939, it was normal for magazines to go on sale before their cover date. One reason is that an advance date fooled customers into thinking that a particular issue was still current, and so secured higher sales. It also told retailers when to remove that issue from sale.</p>
            <p style="line-height:1.7;font-size:14.5px"><em>Detective Comics</em> No. 27 is now widely considered to be one of the most valuable comics in the world. It originally retailed for 10 cents, but the most expensive copy sold at auction for 1,075,000 US dollars in February 2010.</p>
            <p style="opacity:.6;font-size:12.5px;margin-top:8px">Transcripción del audio del examen CPEIP 2024, adaptada para lectura (uso educativo).</p>
          </details>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">What is the recording mainly about?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> How to draw comic-book superheroes step by step.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> A comparison between Batman and Superman as fighters.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> The life story of the actor who played Batman in films.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> The first appearance of Batman and the history of <em>Detective Comics</em> No. 27.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: D.</strong> El episodio relata cuándo y cómo apareció Batman por primera vez y la historia de <em>Detective Comics</em> N.&deg; 27. <strong>A</strong> y <strong>C</strong> no se tratan (no enseña a dibujar ni habla de actores); <strong>B</strong> menciona a Superman solo como antecedente de éxito, sin compararlos como peleadores.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">On what date did Batman make his first appearance?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> In March 1937.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> In May 1939.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> On 30 March 1939.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> In February 2010.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: C.</strong> El podcast abre con <em>"On 30 March 1939 Batman made his first appearance"</em>. <strong>A</strong> es cuando apareció el primer número de <em>Detective Comics</em> (1937); <strong>B</strong> es la "cover date" del N.&deg; 27, distinta de la fecha de venta; <strong>D</strong> es cuando se vendió la copia más cara en subasta.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">Who created Batman, according to the recording?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> Bob Kane and Bill Finger.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> Commissioner Gordon.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> Bruce Wayne.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> National Allied Publications, on its own.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: A.</strong> El audio dice: <em>"Batman was created by Bob Kane and Bill Finger"</em>. <strong>B</strong> es un personaje que aparece en la historia; <strong>C</strong> es el alter ego del propio Batman dentro de la ficción; <strong>D</strong> es la editorial que lo publicó, no quien lo creó.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">According to the narrator, why was it normal for the comic to go on sale before its cover date?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> Because the printers always finished the comics too early.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> Because Batman demanded it in the story.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> Because comics were illegal to sell on their real date.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> Because an advance date made customers think the issue was still current, securing higher sales, and told retailers when to remove it.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: D.</strong> El narrador explica que la fecha adelantada <em>"fooled customers into thinking that a particular issue was still current, and so secured higher sales"</em>, y además indicaba a los vendedores cuándo retirarlo. <strong>A</strong>, <strong>B</strong> y <strong>C</strong> no se mencionan; la razón es comercial, no de imprenta, de la ficción ni legal.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="ec-caso">
            <span class="tag"><i class="bi bi-clipboard2-pulse"></i> Pregunta tipo ECEP · Listening</span>
            <div class="escenario">How much did the most expensive copy of <em>Detective Comics</em> No. 27 sell for at auction?</div>
            <ol>
              <li><b>A)</b> 10 cents, its original retail price.</li>
              <li><b>B)</b> 800,000 copies per issue.</li>
              <li><b>C)</b> 1,075,000 US dollars, in February 2010.</li>
              <li><b>D)</b> 27 dollars, the same as its issue number.</li>
            </ol>
            <button class="reveal">Ver respuesta y explicación</button>
            <div class="a"><strong>Correcta: C.</strong> El cierre dice que <em>"the most expensive copy sold at auction for 1,075,000 US dollars in February 2010"</em>. <strong>A</strong> es el precio original de venta (10 centavos), no el de subasta; <strong>B</strong> confunde el precio con el tiraje de 800.000 copias; <strong>D</strong> mezcla la cifra con el número del cómic.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>


